Shell types:-

  Bourne Shell (sh)
  C Shell (csh or tcsh )
  Korn Shell (ksh)
  Z Shell (Zsh)
  Bourne again Shell (bash) Most popular

To check the Shell in your OS. the command is:-
    echo $SHELL         
    Output is like     /bin/bash


To change the default Shell
command is :-
    Chsh
    Password:
    Changing the login shell for michael
    Enter the new value, or press ENTER for the default Login Shell [/bin/bash]: /bin/sh


Some feature of Bash Shell:-
    Bash auto completion by entering Tab key
    We can set alias e:g syntax:- alias dt=date   so whenever you hit dt then you will get same output as with date.
    we can see command history by history command.

Bash Enivornment Variables
    echo $SHELL         
    Output is like   /bin/bash
    so in this $SHELL is Environment Variable. Variable are same as in any programming language to store some information.
    By using env command you can see all the evironment variables.
    To make a varibale use export command. syntax export office=Toronto

Path variablesn
    To see use command [  echo $PATH   ]
    To set path variable [   export PATH=$PATH:/obs/bin   ]
    you can check by using which command [   which obs studio   ]

Bash prompt

    [~]$
    ~ means present working directory
    $ means user prompt symbol
    
        ubuntu-server: PS1="[\d \t \u@h: \w ]$ "
        
        Output is below
        [Thu Mar 12 22:12:54 bob@caleston: ~ 1 $
    
    These are the arguments below: -
      Id: the date in "Weekday Month Date" format (e.g., "Tue May 26")
      le: an ASCIl escape character (033)
      \h: the hostname HQDN \H: the complete hostname
      In : newline
      Ir: carriage return
      Is: the name of the shell
      It : the current time in 24-hour HH:MM:SS format
      \T : the current time in 12-hour HH:MM:SS format
      1@: the current time in 12-hour am/pm format
      IA: the current time in 24-hour HH:MM format lu : the username of the current user
      Iw : the current working directory, with $HOME abbreviated with a tilde IW: the basename of the current working directory, with $HOME abbreviated with a tilde
      1$: if the effective UID is 0, a #, otherwise a $
